<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="417" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[160,1156,1279,1513]" box="[160,286,1279,1305]" pageId="2" pageNumber="417">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,286,1279,1305]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="417">Comments</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[160,1156,1279,1513]" pageId="2" pageNumber="417">
The endogyne of the 
<typeStatus box="[415,515,1315,1340]" pageId="2" pageNumber="417">holotype</typeStatus>
female of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kulczynski" authorityYear="1895" box="[643,767,1315,1340]" class="Arachnida" family="Dictynidae" genus="Dictyna" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="417" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ignobilis">
<emphasis box="[643,767,1315,1340]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="417">D. ignobilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is undistinguishable from that of 
<taxonomicName box="[160,329,1350,1375]" class="Arachnida" family="Dictynidae" genus="Dictyna" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="417" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arundinacea">
<emphasis box="[160,329,1350,1375]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="417">D. arundinacea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The adult male specimen collected about 10 kilometres from the type locality has no distinct differences in the palp from that of 
<taxonomicName box="[822,989,1384,1409]" class="Arachnida" family="Dictynidae" genus="Dictyna" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="417" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arundinacea">
<emphasis box="[822,989,1384,1409]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="417">D. arundinacea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and therefore the two names are synonymised here. The slight apparent differences between the male palps of specimens from 
<collectingCountry box="[445,540,1454,1479]" name="Armenia" pageId="2" pageNumber="417">Armenia</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[555,686,1454,1479]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="3.[160,225,1391,1414]" captionTargetBox="[169,1150,144,1354]" captionTargetId="figure-54@3.[163,1153,142,1359]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figure 2. Males of Dictyna arundinacea from the type locality of D. ignobilis (a–d, g–h) and from Yakutia (e–f). (a) male palp, prolateral view; (b, e) male palp, ventral view; (c, f) male palp, retrolateral view; (d, g–h) male, dorsal, lateral, and frontal views. Scale bars = 0.2 mm unless otherwise indicated." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6758515" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6758515/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="417">Figure 2a–c</figureCitation>
) and Yakutia (
<figureCitation box="[849,983,1454,1479]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="3.[160,225,1391,1414]" captionTargetBox="[169,1150,144,1354]" captionTargetId="figure-54@3.[163,1153,142,1359]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figure 2. Males of Dictyna arundinacea from the type locality of D. ignobilis (a–d, g–h) and from Yakutia (e–f). (a) male palp, prolateral view; (b, e) male palp, ventral view; (c, f) male palp, retrolateral view; (d, g–h) male, dorsal, lateral, and frontal views. Scale bars = 0.2 mm unless otherwise indicated." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6758515" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6758515/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="417">Figure 2d–e</figureCitation>
) are caused by different positions of the palps during photography.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="417" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="2.[160,1155,1564,1728]" box="[160,300,1564,1590]" pageId="2" pageNumber="417">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,300,1564,1590]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="417">Distribution</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[160,1155,1564,1728]" pageId="2" pageNumber="417">
<taxonomicName box="[160,380,1599,1624]" class="Arachnida" family="Dictynidae" genus="Dictyna" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="417" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arundinacea">
<emphasis box="[160,380,1599,1624]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="417">Dictyna arundinacea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a circum-Holarctic range and is known across the whole Palaearctic from 
<collectingCountry box="[220,299,1634,1659]" name="Iceland" pageId="2" pageNumber="417">Iceland</collectingCountry>
to Kamchatka (
<bibRefCitation author="Marusik YM &amp; Logunov DV &amp; Koponen S" box="[471,680,1634,1659]" pageId="2" pageNumber="417" refId="ref2414" refString="Marusik YM, Logunov DV, Koponen S. 2000. Spiders of Tuva, south Siberia. Institute for Biological Problems of the North, Magadan, 253 pp." type="book" year="2000">Marusik et al. 2000</bibRefCitation>
), and throughout the Nearctic from Alaska (GenBank accession nos: 
<accessionNumber box="[436,550,1669,1694]" httpUri="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nucleotide/KU874826" pageId="2" pageNumber="417">KU874826</accessionNumber>
, 
<accessionNumber box="[560,673,1669,1694]" httpUri="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nucleotide/KU874827" pageId="2" pageNumber="417">KU874827</accessionNumber>
) to Newfoundland (
<bibRefCitation author="Paquin P &amp; Buckle DJ &amp; Duperre N &amp; Dondale CD" box="[893,1091,1669,1694]" pageId="2" pageNumber="417" pagination="1 - 170" refId="ref2538" refString="Paquin P, Buckle DJ, Duperre N, Dondale CD. 2010. Checklist of the spiders (Araneae) of Canada and Alaska. Zootaxa. 2461 (1): 1 - 170. doi: 10.11646 / zootaxa. 2461.1.1." type="journal article" year="2010">Paquin et al. 2010</bibRefCitation>
). This species is also known from across the Caucasus, including 
<collectingCountry box="[804,897,1703,1728]" name="Armenia" pageId="2" pageNumber="417">Armenia</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Otto S" box="[910,1022,1703,1728]" pageId="2" pageNumber="417" pagination="20" refId="ref2505" refString="Otto S. 2022. Caucasian Spiders. A faunistic database on the spiders of the Caucasus. Version 02.2022 Internet: accessed 2022 Mar 20. https: // caucasus-spiders. info" type="journal article" year="2022">Otto 2022</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
